<subSubSection id="C32F65354E0EFFC897D80524FD2342A0" pageId="41" pageNumber="242" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="8B8A36BE4E0EFFC897D80524FD2342A0" blockId="41.[151,1437,762,2011]" pageId="41" pageNumber="242">
<emphasis id="B941EAAC4E0EFFC897D80524FEDD42E8" bold="true" box="[199,334,1914,1939]" pageId="41" pageNumber="242">Etymology.</emphasis>
“ 
<emphasis id="B941EAAC4E0EFFC8967B0525FE2E42E9" box="[356,445,1915,1938]" italics="true" pageId="41" pageNumber="242">Luze-cu</emphasis>
” is a popular name by which fireflies in 
<collectingCountry id="F322762E4E0EFFC894800524FC7042E8" box="[927,995,1914,1939]" name="Brazil" pageId="41" pageNumber="242">Brazil</collectingCountry>
are referred to, especially in the rural municipalities (
<bibRefCitation id="EFA44B4F4E0EFFC8965705C0FDEC42CC" author="Lenko" box="[328,639,1950,1975]" pageId="41" pageNumber="242" refString="Lenko, K. &amp; Papavero, N. (1996) Insetos no Folclore. (Pleiade, Sao Paulo), 468 pp." type="book" year="1996">
Lenko and Papavero 
<number id="3DFD24994E0EFFC8955C05C0FDEC42CC" box="[579,639,1950,1975]" pageId="41" pageNumber="242" value="1996.0">1996</number>
</bibRefCitation>
). 
<collectingCountry id="F322762E4E0EFFC8958805C1FD2542CC" box="[663,694,1951,1975]" name="American Samoa" pageId="41" pageNumber="242">As</collectingCountry>
the name suggests, it is based on the common knowledge that fireflies “light their bums”. Name in apposition.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
